<TITLE> Stocks end flat </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jul 8 (bdnews24.com)Stocks closed near-flat on Wednesday, although reports of new legislation boosted insurance scrips, while banks ended mixed. Dhaka Stock Exchange's benchmark closed just 2 points up, while the Chittagong Stock Exchange's key index lost around 25 points. Observers said heavy buying in insurance took place on reports of the new insurance act going to parliament for ratification. Observers said the new law could cause insurers to hike their capital substantially. Meanwhile, some banking heavyweights rose, while others continued to edge down. "Major banking shares witnessed buying in the wake of lower prices," said an official of brokerage firm Royal Securities, asking not to be named. Power and energy shares also made their way into the buying basket, with most of the mutual funds following suit. ICT shares lost on profit taking, after gaining for the last three days. Dhaka stocks rose in the first hour, slumping in the midday session, before buying in the latter part of the day caused the key index to close even. Turnover on the bourses rose flowing loses over the last two days, with the DSE passing the Tk 7 billion mark and the CSE above Tk 900 million. The DSE's turnover jumped to Tk 7.12 billion from Tk 5.41 billion Tuesday. DSE general index or DGEN edged up 2.32 points, or 0.07 percent, to close at 2959.52. The DSI or all share price index crawled to 2475.70, up by 2.12 points, or 0.08 percent. The blue chip DSE-20 slumped 42.08 points, or 1.75 percent, to end on 2350.29, contributed by heavy falloffs in Square Pharmaceuticals. Of the scrips traded, 116 gained, 108 lost and six remained unchanged. Square Pharmaceuticals closed as turnover leader on reports of its upcoming corporate declaration. It saw shares worth Tk 603,326 million traded, slumping 8.26 percent to Tk 3220.75. The company declared 40 percent cash dividend and 25 percent stock dividend for its shareholders. Market observers said the declaration dashed higher investors' expectations. Titas Gas followed with a turnover of Tk 586,986 million, gaining 1.70 percent to end on 686.25. Banking sector bigwig AB Bank had Tk 442,886 million in turnover, ending on Tk 1,007, surging 5.58 percent following Tuesday's losses. Beximco saw Tk 403,797 million worth of shares traded, slipping 0.54 percent to close at Tk 294.30. Fareast Life Insurance ended on Tk 3274.75, up by 3.72 percent. Shares worth Tk 249.367 million changed hands. Among the other scrips on the turnover board  Beximco Pharmaceuticals, Summit Power, BD Online and Islami Bank fell on profit taking. Buying pressure caused Atlas Bangladesh Ltd to gain from the previous day. Chittagong Stocks Losses in pharmaceuticals, engineering and services' shares along with the blue chips caused the indices to end lower. The CSCX or selective categories index dropped 66.93 points, or 0.82 percent, to close at 6621.35. The CASPI or all share price index ended on 10234.07, losing 44.59 points, or 0.43 percent. The CSE-30 blue chip ended on 8037.64, falling 66.93 points or 0.82 percent. Losers beat gainers by 81 to 66 and three scrips holding steady. Turnover on the port city bourse went up to Tk 909,179 million from the previous day's total of Tk 745,799 million. AB Bank remained top the turnover board, with shares of Tk 1.52 billion changing hands. Square Pharmaceuticals, Beximco Ltd, Titas Gas and Beximco Pharmaceuticals were the other turnover leaders
